[2] Sierra Leone: urges safe burials to stem Ebola
Date: Sun 21 Dec 2014
Source: ABC News, AP (Associated Press) report [edited]
http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/sierra-leone-urges-safe-burials-stem-ebola-27746120


Sierra Leonians urge safe burials to stem Ebola
-----------------------------------------------
Dr Desmond Williams, a Sierra Leonean-American doctor who works for the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention [CDC], took to the airwaves in November 2014 as part of efforts to encourage people to avoid dangerous burial practices. Now similar pledges have been made by prominent Sierra Leoneans, including the communications director for the Health Ministry, pop stars and radio DJ's. Dr Williams' radio announcement is chilling and blunt:

"If I die, I want the deaths to stop with me. I want to give my family the permission to request a safe and dignified, medical burial for me."

The announcement is part of a [radio] campaign to urge Sierra Leoneans to abandon traditional burial practices, such as relatives touching or washing the dead bodies, that are fueling the spread of Ebola in the West African country. Unsafe burials may be responsible for up to 70 per cent of new infections, say experts.

But cultural traditions are hard to break. Many believe a traditional burial is necessary to make sure the dead don't return to haunt the living. A well-attended funeral where many people touch the body provides the opportunity for the disease to disperse into a crowd and then be carried long distances back to their homes, where it can seed new clusters, according to Rebecca Bunnell, a behavioral epidemiologist with CDC. People have been washing their hands more and avoiding crowded places, but changing burial traditions has proven particularly hard. "Burials and funerals are deeply, deeply ingrained in Sierra Leone," said Austin Demby, a Sierra Leonean-American epidemiologist who has also taken the burial pledge. He is the director of a US government AIDS program but has been helping with Ebola containment.

In the early days of the Ebola epidemic, some families held their own burials because teams were slow to arrive, or carried off bodies without telling relatives where they would be buried, said Bunnell of CDC. But as more teams have been put in the field and relatives have increasingly been able to watch funerals, compliance appears to be increasing...

[byline: Sarah DiLorenzo]

