[4] Sierra Leone: treatment with ORS for suspect Ebola cases, rapid tests
Date: Wed 17 Dec 2014
From: Katrina Roper <katrina@ivelo.net> [edited]


I would like to provide clarification on the comment provided by moderator JW -- "Why not treat all severe fever cases in those countries now with ORS (oral rehydration solution) as long as they can still take liquid by mouth?" -- see ProMED-mail. Ebola virus disease - ex Africa (53): Canada, Netherlands, susp. 20141217.3037779.

I have recently returned from Sierra Leone, after 6 weeks in-country [September-October 2014] providing social mobilisation and IPC/PPE training to health care workers. During my time there, I visited several Ebola observation and treatment units, and also discussed strategies with the staff running the facilities. I can state that in the units in Freetown, Sierra Leone, particularly those run by the Sierra Leone staff, the standard response is to immediately commence ORS, along with anti-malarials, antibiotics and vitamins, upon admission of any patient. The strategy is to provide immediate supportive treatment to give the patients the best chance of survival.

As moderator JW observes, it is the same strategy as per treatment of cholera patients; keep the patients as hydrated as possible by ORS while they can still take liquids by mouth. Where the rapid test will be very useful will be in screening at observation units, to more rapidly identify those who have EVD and hence need to be moved to a treatment unit as a confirmed case, and to more rapidly release those who do not have the virus, hence freeing up a bed to isolate another suspect or probable case.

The rapid test will also be useful at hospital triage to help identify potential EVD patients who have presented ostensibly for another illness, for example, a vomiting pregnant woman. Being able to identify EVD positive patients more rapidly will help staff work more safely and provide appropriate care.

--
Dr Katrina Roper
PhD, MAppEpid
<katrina@ivelo.net>

[ProMED is always pleased to receive 1st-hand reports of outbreaks. Dr Roper is a WHO consultant and says she will be returning to the field. - Mod.JW]

