[6] Region: Ebola-stricken families to receive cash payments
Date: Fri Dec 19 2014
Source: Time [edited]
http://time.com/3642240/ebola-cash-payments


Ebola- stricken families to receive cash payments
-------------------------------------------------
In 2015, the 3 Ebola-affected countries will start offering cash payments for families hit by Ebola, as well as survivors having trouble re-acclimating to society because of the stigma of the disease.

Every aspect of Guinea, Liberia and Sierra Leone's societies have taken a hit from Ebola, and the disease has shocked what were once fragile but growing economies. Public spaces are now forbidden, so markets are empty, tourists are no longer traveling into the countries and international companies have largely pulled out, including large industries like mining. The World Bank estimates the aftershock of Ebola to already weakened economies will be "devastating".

"We are seeing a backwards slide of development of about 10 years," says Boaz Paldi, chief of media and advocacy at the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP). "The outlook is not good." That's why instead of waiting for caseloads to reach manageable numbers, the 3 countries, with the help of UNDP and other partners, are laying the groundwork now for rebuilding the damaged economies. One of the 1st major initiatives to be rolled out in the new year [2015] are cash transfers and payments to families who no longer have breadwinners, and to survivors out of work. Many women in the Ebola-affected countries have taken in orphaned children of their family members or neighbors, despite having no steady income.

UNDP has calculated that around USD 50 will keep a family of 5 going in the 3 countries with essential needs for one month, with some variations by country. The group is anticipating making monthly payments to 150-200 thousand people in each of the countries.

According to UNDP leaders, plans for the payment process are still being refined. Lists of names of affected families and survivors are being collected and coordinated for small pilot programs, starting early 2015, to test the effectiveness of the payments in preparation for widespread efforts...

[byline: Alexandra Sifferlin]

